### You can set Google Chrome&#39;s cookies if your project type is ASP.Net-related.

If you&#39;re making a backend software just add new header to your response:

``` CSharp
public void Test()
{
     Response.Cookies.Append(&quot;ExampleCookie&quot;, &quot;Cookie value!&quot;);
}
```

### You can&#39;t natively set Google Chrome&#39;s cookies from C# if browser is running side-to-side your application on one pc.&lt;br/&gt;
I don&#39;t really say you can&#39;t, but you really shouldn&#39;t do this. Because:&lt;br/&gt;

1) You need to find how cookies are stored in files&lt;br/&gt;
2) You need to modify them. Structures can change on any browser update.&lt;br/&gt;
3) It can trigger antivirus software. What if your application is trying to steal something from browser?

JavaScript only executes in the context of your page, it has access to internal API, so yes, it&#39;s much easier to do in JS.

You can use [embedded browser for WinForms][1] or you can embed [CefSharp][2] browser (Chromium engine).&lt;br/&gt;
You can easily modify cookies of these browsers (that run in the context of your application).


  [1]: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.windows.forms.webbrowser
  [2]: https://github.com/cefsharp/CefSharp

